What @{b}configure@{ub} does
*******************

   This manual documents Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub}, a program which helps to
automate much of the setup activity associated with building large
suites of programs, such the Cygnus Support Developer's Kit.  This
manual is therefore geared toward readers who are likely to face the
problem of configuring software in source form before compiling and
installing it.  We assume you are an experienced programmer or system
administrator.  For further background on this topic, see
@{"Apologia Configure" link "cfg-paper.guide/Some Basic Terms"}, by K. Richard Pixley.

   When @{b}configure@{ub} runs, it does the following things:

@{i}* creates build directories@{ui}
     When you run @{b}configure@{ub} with the @{b}--srcdir@{ub} option, it uses the
     current directory as the @{i}build directory@{ui}, creating under it a
     directory tree that parallels the directory structure of the
     source directory.  If you don't specify a @{b}srcdir@{ub}, @{b}configure@{ub} first
     assumes that the source code you wish to configure is in your
     current directory; if it finds no @{b}configure.in@{ub} input file there,
     it searches in the directory @{b}configure@{ub} itself lies in.  (For
     details, see @{"Build directories" link "Build directories"}.)

@{i}* generates @{b}Makefile@{ub}@{ui}
     A @{b}Makefile@{ub} template from the source directory, usually called
     @{b}Makefile.in@{ub}, is copied to an output file in the build directory
     which is most often named @{b}Makefile@{ub}.  @{b}configure@{ub} places definitions
     for a number of standard @{b}Makefile@{ub} macros at the beginning of the
     output file.  If @{b}--prefix=DIR@{ub} or @{b}--exec_prefix=DIR@{ub} are specified
     on the @{b}configure@{ub} command line, corresponding @{b}Makefile@{ub} variables
     are set accordingly.  If host, target, or site-specific @{b}Makefile@{ub}
     fragments exist, these are inserted into the output file.  (For
     details, see @{"Makefile generation" link "Makefile generation"}.)

@{i}* generates @{b}.gdbinit@{ub}@{ui}
     If the source directory contains a @{b}.gdbinit@{ub} file and the build
     directory is not the same as the source directory, a @{b}.gdbinit@{ub} file
     is created in the build directory.  This @{b}.gdbinit@{ub} file contains
     commands which allow the source directory to be read when
     debugging with the GNU debugger, @{b}gdb@{ub}.  (See @{"Command Files" link "gdb.guide/Command Files"}.)

@{i}* makes symbolic links@{ui}
     Most build directories require that some symbolic links with
     generic names are built pointing to specific files in the source
     directory.  If the system where @{b}configure@{ub} runs cannot support
     symbolic links, hard links are used instead.  (For details, see
     @{"The configure.in input file" link "configure.in"}.)

@{i}* generates @{b}config.status@{ub}@{ui}
@{b}     configure@{ub} creates a shell script named @{b}config.status@{ub} in the build
     directory.  This shell script, when run from the build directory
     (usually from within a @{b}Makefile@{ub}), will reconfigure the build
     directory (but not its subdirectories).  This is most often used
     to have a @{b}Makefile@{ub} update itself automatically if a new source
     directory is available.

@{i}* calls itself recursively@{ui}
     If the source directory has subdirectories that should also be
     configured, @{b}configure@{ub} is called for each.


@endnode

