Invoking @{b}configure@{ub}
******************

   Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub} is a shell script which resides in a source tree.
The usual way to invoke @{b}configure@{ub} is from the shell, as follows:

     eg$ ./configure HOSTTYPE

This prepares the source in the current directory (@{b}.@{ub}) to be compiled
for a HOSTTYPE environment.  It assumes that you wish to build programs
and files in the default @{i}build directory@{ui} (also the current directory,
@{b}.@{ub}).  If you do not specify a value for HOSTTYPE, Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub} will
attempt to discover this information by itself (see
@{"Determining system information" link "config.guess"}).  For information on HOSTTYPE
environments, See @{"Host" link "Host"}.

   All GNU software is packaged with one or more @{b}configure@{ub} script(s)
(see @{"How Configuration Should Work" link "standards.guide/Configuration"}).  By using @{b}configure@{ub} you prepare
the source for your specific environment by selecting and using
@{b}Makefile@{ub} fragments and fragments of shell scripts, which are prepared
in advance and stored with the source.

@{b}   configure@{ub}'s command-line options also allow you to specify other
aspects of the source configuration:

       configure HOSTTYPE  [--target=TARGET] [--srcdir=DIR] [--rm]
                 [--site=SITE] [--prefix=DIR] [--exec-prefix=DIR]
                 [--program-prefix=STRING] [--tmpdir=DIR]
                 [--with-PACKAGE[=YES/NO]] [--without-PACKAGE]
                 [--enable-FEATURE[=YES/NO]] [--disable-FEATURE]
                 [--norecursion] [--nfp] [-s] [-v] [-V | --version] [--help]

@{b}--target=TARGET@{ub}
     Requests that the sources be configured to target the TARGET
     machine.  If no target is specified explicitly, the target is
     assumed to be the same as the host (i.e., a @{i}native@{ui} configuration).
     See @{"Host" link "Host"}, and @{"Target" link "Target"}, for discussions of each.

@{b}--srcdir=DIR@{ub}
     Direct each generated @{b}Makefile@{ub} to use the sources located in
     directory DIR.  Use this option whenever you wish the object code
     to reside in a different place from the source code.  The @{i}build
     directory@{ui} is always assumed to be the directory you call @{b}configure@{ub}
     from.  See @{"Build directories" link "Build directories"}, for an example.  If the source
     directory is not specified, @{b}configure@{ub} assumes that the source is
     in your current directory.  If @{b}configure@{ub} finds no @{b}configure.in@{ub}
     there, it searches in the same directory that the @{b}configure@{ub} script
     itself lies in.  Pathnames specified (Values for DIR) can be
     either absolute relative to the @{i}build@{ui} directory.

@{b}--rm@{ub}
@{i}     Remove@{ui} the configuration specified by HOSTTYPE and the other
     command-line options, rather than create it.

@{i}          Note:@{ui} We recommend that you use @{b}make distclean@{ub} rather than
          use this option; see @{"Invoking make" link "make.guide/Invoking make"}, for details on @{b}make
          distclean@{ub}.

@{b}--site=SITE@{ub}
     Generate the @{b}Makefile@{ub} using site-specific @{b}Makefile@{ub} fragments for
     SITE.  See @{"Adding information about local conventions" link "Makefile fragments"}.

@{b}--prefix=DIR@{ub}
     Configure the source to install programs and files under directory
     DIR.

     This option sets the variable @{b}prefix@{ub}.  Each generated @{b}Makefile@{ub}
     will have its @{b}prefix@{ub} variables set to this value.  (See
     @{"What configure really does" link "What configure really does"}.)

@{b}--exec-prefix=DIR@{ub}
     Configure the source to install @{i}host dependent@{ui} files in DIR.

     This option sets the variable @{b}exec_prefix@{ub}.  Each generated
     @{b}Makefile@{ub} will have its @{b}exec_prefix@{ub} variables set to this value.
     (See @{"What configure really does" link "What configure really does"}.)

@{b}--program-prefix=STRING@{ub}
     Configure the source to install certain programs using STRING as a
     prefix.  This applies to programs which might be used for
     cross-compilation, such as the compiler and the binary utilities,
     and also to programs which have the same names as common Unix
     programs, such as @{b}make@{ub}.

     This option sets the variable @{b}program_prefix@{ub}.  Each generated
     @{b}Makefile@{ub} will have its @{b}program_prefix@{ub} variables set to this value.
     (See @{"What configure really does" link "What configure really does"}.)

@{b}--tmpdir=TMPDIR@{ub}
     Use the directory TMPDIR for @{b}configure@{ub}'s temporary files.  The
     default is the value of the environment variable @{b}TMPDIR@{ub}, or @{b}/tmp@{ub}
     if the environment variable is not set.

@{b}--with-PACKAGE[=YES/NO]@{ub}
@{b}--without-PACKAGE@{ub}
     Indicate that PACKAGE is present, or not present, depending on
     YES/NO.  If YES/NO is nonexistent, its value is assumed to be @{b}yes@{ub}.
     @{b}--without-PACKAGE@{ub} is equivalent to @{b}--with-PACKAGE=no@{ub}.

     For example, if you wish to configure the program @{b}gcc@{ub} for a Sun
     SPARCstation running SunOS 4.x, and you want @{b}gcc@{ub} to use the GNU
     linker @{b}ld@{ub}, you can configure @{b}gcc@{ub} using

          eg$ configure --with-gnu-ld sun4

     See @{"What configure really does" link "What configure really does"}, for details.  See the
     installation or release notes for your particular package for
     details on which other PACKAGE options are recognized.

@{b}--enable-FEATURE[=YES/NO]@{ub}
@{b}--disable-FEATURE@{ub}
     Include FEATURE, or not, depending on YES/NO.  If YES/NO is
     nonexistent, its value is assumed to be @{b}yes@{ub}.  @{b}--disable-FEATURE@{ub} is
     equivalent to @{b}--enable-FEATURE=no@{ub}.

     See @{"What configure really does" link "What configure really does"}, for details.  See the
     installation or release notes for your particular package for
     details on which other FEATURE options are recognized.

@{b}--norecursion@{ub}
     Configure only this directory; ignore any subdirectories.  This is
     used by the executable shell script @{b}config.status@{ub} to reconfigure
     only the current directory; it is most often used
     non-interactively, when @{b}make@{ub} is invoked.  (See @{"config.status" link "config.status"}.)

@{b}--nfp@{ub}
     Assume that the intended HOSTTYPE has no floating point unit.

@{b}-s@{ub}
     Suppress status output.  This option is used internally by
     @{b}configure@{ub} when calling itself recursively in subdirectories.  You
     can override this option with the @{b}--verbose@{ub} option.

@{b}-v@{ub}
@{b}--verbose@{ub}
     Print status lines for each directory configured.  Normally, only
     the status lines for the initial working directory are printed.

@{b}--version@{ub}
@{b}-V@{ub}
     Print the @{b}configure@{ub} version number.

@{b}--help@{ub}
     Print a short summary of how to invoke @{b}configure@{ub}.

@{i}   Note:@{ui} You may introduce options with a single dash, @{b}-@{ub}, rather than
two dashes, @{b}--@{ub}.  However, you may not be able to truncate long option
names when using a single dash.  When using two dashes, options may be
abbreviated as long as each option can be uniquely identified.  For
example,
     eg$ configure --s=/u/me/src HOSTTYPE

is ambiguous, as @{b}--s@{ub} could refer to either @{b}--site@{ub} or @{b}--srcdir@{ub}.  However,
     eg$ configure --src=/u/me/src HOSTTYPE

is a valid abbreviation.


@endnode

