What @{b}configure@{ub} really does
==========================

   Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub} is a shell script that sets up an environment in
which your programs will compile correctly for your machine and
operating system, and will install in proper places.  @{b}configure@{ub}
accomplishes this task by doing the following:

   * it generates a @{b}Makefile@{ub} from a custom template called @{b}Makefile.in@{ub}
     in each relevant source directory;

   * it customizes the build process to your specifications; you set
     certain variables for @{b}configure@{ub}, either on the command line or in
     the file @{b}configure.in@{ub}, which subsequently sets variables in each
     generated @{b}Makefile@{ub} to be used by @{b}make@{ub} when actually building the
     software;

   * it creates @{i}build directories@{ui}, places for your code to be compiled
     in before being installed;

   * it generates a @{b}.gdbinit@{ub} in the build directory, if needed, to
     communicate to @{b}gdb@{ub} where to find the program's source code;

   * it generates a shell script called @{b}config.status@{ub} which is used
     most often by the @{b}Makefile@{ub} to reconfigure itself;

   * it recurses in subdirectories, setting up entire trees so that
     they build correctly; if @{b}configure@{ub} finds another @{b}configure@{ub} script
     further down in a given source tree, it knows to use this script
     and not recur.

   For the sake of safety (i.e., in order to prevent broken
installations), the GNU coding standards call for software to be
@{i}configured@{ui} in such a way that an end user trying to build a given
package will be able to do so by affecting a finite number of
variables.  All GNU software comes with an executable @{b}configure@{ub} shell
script which sets up an environment within a build directory which will
correctly compile your new package for your host (or, alternatively,
whatever host you specify to @{b}configure@{ub}).  For further background on
this topic, see @{"Apologia Configure" link "cfg-paper.guide/Some Basic Terms"}, by K. Richard Pixley.

   Use @{b}configure@{ub} to set for the build process:

   * correct values for certain variables;

   * which type of host you wish to configure a given package for (see
     @{"Host" link "Host"});

   * where you want to install this package (by using @{b}prefix@{ub},
     @{b}exec-prefix@{ub} and @{b}program-prefix@{ub}; see
     @{"Full descriptions of all installation directories" link "Install details"});

   * optionally, which type of machine you wish to @{i}target@{ui} this
     package's output to (see @{"Target" link "Target"});

   * which other GNU packages are already installed and available to
     this particular build (by using the @{b}--with-PACKAGE@{ub} option; see
     @{"Invoking configure" link "Invoking configure"});

   * where to place temporary files (by using the @{b}--tmpdir=DIR@{ub} option;
     see @{"Invoking configure" link "Invoking configure"});

   * whether to recur in subdirectories (changeable through the
     @{b}--norecursion@{ub} option; see @{"Invoking configure" link "Invoking configure"}).

@{b}   configure@{ub} uses a few other files to complete its tasks.  These are
discussed in detail where noted.

@{b}configure.in@{ub}
     Input file for @{b}configure@{ub}.  Shell script fragments reside here.
     See @{"The configure.in input file" link "configure.in"}.

@{b}Makefile.in@{ub}
     Template which @{b}configure@{ub} uses to build a file called @{b}Makefile@{ub} in
     the @{i}build directory@{ui}.  See @{"Makefile generation" link "Makefile generation"}.

@{b}config.sub@{ub}
     Shell script used by @{b}configure@{ub} to expand referents to the HOSTTYPE
     argument into a single specification of the form CPU-VENDOR-OS.
     For instance, on the command line you can specify

          eg$ ./configure sun4

     to configure for a Sun SPARCstation running SunOS 4.x.  @{b}configure@{ub}
     consults @{b}config.sub@{ub} to find that the three-part specification for
     this is

          sparc-sun-sunos4.1.1

     which notes the CPU as @{b}sparc@{ub}, the MANUFACTURER as @{b}sun@{ub} (Sun
     Microsystems), and the OS (operating system) as @{b}sunos4.1.1@{ub}, the
     SunOS 4.1.1 release.  See @{"Variables available to configure" link "configure variables"}.

@{b}config.guess@{ub}
     If you do not put the HOSTTYPE argument on the command line,
     @{b}configure@{ub} uses the @{b}config.guess@{ub} shell script to make an analysis
     of your machine (it assumes that you wish to configure your
     software for the type of machine on which you are running).  The
     output of @{b}config.guess@{ub} is a three-part identifier as described
     above.

@{b}config.status@{ub}
     The final step in configuring a directory is to create a shell
     script, @{b}config.status@{ub}.  The main purpose of this file is to allow
     the @{b}Makefile@{ub} for the current directory to rebuild itself, if
     necessary.  See @{"config.status" link "config.status"}.

@{b}config/*@{ub}
@{b}     configure@{ub} uses three types of @{b}Makefile@{ub} @{i}fragments@{ui}, which reside in
     the directory @{b}SRCDIR/config/@{ub}.  See
     @{"Adding information about local conventions" link "Makefile fragments"}.


