Build variables
---------------

   There are several variables in the build process which you can
control through build programs such as @{b}make@{ub}.  These include machine
definitions, local conventions, installation locations, locations for
temporary files, etc.  This data is accessible through certain
variables which are configurable in the build process; we refer to them
as @{i}build variables@{ui}.

   For lists of build variables which you can affect by using @{b}configure@{ub},
see @{"Variables available to configure.in" link "configure variables"}, and
@{"Full descriptions of all installation directories" link "Install details"}.

   Generally, build variables, which are used by the @{b}Makefile@{ub} to
determine various aspects of the build and installation processes, are
changeable with command-line options to @{b}configure@{ub}.  In most large
suites of programs, like the Cygnus Support Developer's Kit, the
individual programs reside in several subdirectories of a single source
code "tree".  All of these subdirectories need to be configured with
information relative to the @{i}build directory@{ui}, which is not known until
@{b}configure@{ub} is run.  Unless specified otherwise, @{b}configure@{ub} recursively
configures every subdirectory in the source tree.

   Build variables are passed from @{b}configure@{ub} directly into the
@{b}Makefile@{ub}, and use the same names (except that dashes are transformed
into underbars; for example, when you specify the option @{b}--exec-prefix@{ub}
on the command line, the @{b}Makefile@{ub} variable @{b}exec_prefix@{ub} is set).  In
other words, if you specify

     eg$ ./configure --prefix=/usr/gnu/local ... HOSTTYPE

on the command line, @{b}configure@{ub} sets an variable called @{b}prefix@{ub} to
@{b}/usr/gnu/local@{ub}, and passes this into the @{b}Makefile@{ub} in the same manner.
After this command, each @{b}Makefile@{ub} generated by @{b}configure@{ub} will contain a
line that reads:

     prefix = /usr/gnu/local

   For a list of the @{b}Makefile@{ub} variables @{b}configure@{ub} can change, and
instructions on how to change them, see
@{"Variables available to configure.in" link "configure variables"}, and @{"Invoking configure" link "Invoking configure"}.


@endnode

