@{b}Makefile@{ub} generation
-------------------

   Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub} creates a file called @{b}Makefile@{ub} in the build
directory which can be used with @{b}make@{ub} to automatically build a given
program or package.  @{b}configure@{ub} also builds a @{b}Makefile@{ub} for each relevant
subdirectory for a given program or package (irrelevant subdirectories
would be those which contain no code which needs configuring, and which
therefore have no @{b}configure@{ub} input file @{b}configure.in@{ub} and no @{b}Makefile@{ub}
template @{b}Makefile.in@{ub}).  See @{"make Invocation" link "make.guide/Running"}, for details on using @{b}make@{ub}
to compile your source code.

   Each @{b}Makefile@{ub} contains variables which have been configured for a
specific build.  These build variables are determined when @{b}configure@{ub} is
run.  All build variables have defaults.  By default, @{b}configure@{ub}
generates a @{b}Makefile@{ub} which specifies:

   * a @{i}native@{ui} build, which is to occur

   * in the current directory, and which will be installed

   * in the default installation directory (@{b}/gg@{ub}) when the code is
     compiled with @{b}make@{ub}.

Variables are changeable through command-line options to @{b}configure@{ub} (see
@{"Invoking configure" link "Invoking configure"}).

   If you are porting a new program and intend to use @{b}configure@{ub}, see
@{"Porting with configure" link "Porting"}, as well as @{"Writing Makefiles" link "make.guide/Makefiles"}, and
@{"Makefile Conventions" link "standards.guide/Makefiles"}.


@endnode

@node "config.guess" "configure.guide/config.guess"
@next "config.status"
@prev "Makefile generation"
@toc "What configure really does"

Determining system information
------------------------------

   The shell script @{b}config.guess@{ub} is called when you do not specify a
HOSTTYPE on the command line to @{b}configure@{ub}.  @{b}config.guess@{ub} acquires
available system information from your local machine through the shell
command @{b}uname@{ub}.  It compares this information to a database and attempts
to determine a usable three-part system identifier (known as a @{i}triple@{ui})
to use as your HOSTTYPE.  See @{"What configure really does" link "What configure really does"}, to see how
this information is used.

@{i}   Note:@{ui}  If you do not specify a HOSTTYPE on the command line,
@{b}configure@{ub} will attempt to configure your software to run on the machine
you happen to be using.  This may not be the configuration you desire.


@endnode

@node "config.status" "configure.guide/config.status"
@prev "config.guess"
@toc "What configure really does"

@{b}config.status@{ub}
-------------

   The final step in configuring a directory is to create an executable
shell script, @{b}config.status@{ub}.  The main purpose of this file is to allow
the @{b}Makefile@{ub} for the current directory to rebuild itself, if necessary.
It is usually run from within the @{b}Makefile@{ub}.  See
@{"Extensions to the GNU coding standards" link "Makefile extensions"}.

@{b}   config.status@{ub} also contains a record of the @{b}configure@{ub} session which
created it.


@endnode

@node "configure.in" "configure.guide/configure.in"
@next "Install locations"
@prev "What configure really does"
@toc "Using configure"

The @{b}configure.in@{ub} input file
===========================

   A @{b}configure.in@{ub} file for Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub} consists of a
@{i}per-invocation@{ui} section, followed by a @{i}per-host@{ui} section, followed by a
@{i}per-target@{ui} section, optionally followed by a @{i}post-target@{ui} section.  Each
section is a shell script fragment, which is executed by the @{b}configure@{ub}
shell script at an appropriate time.  Values are passed among @{b}configure@{ub}
and the shell fragments through a set of shell variables.  When each
section is being interpreted by the shell, the shell's current
directory is the build directory, and any files created by the section
(or referred to by the section) will be relative to the build
directory.  To reference files in other places (such as the source
directory), prepend a shell variable such as @{b}$(srcdir)/@{ub} to the desired
file name.

   The beginning of the @{b}configure.in@{ub} file begins the @{i}per-invocation@{ui}
section.

   A line beginning with @{b}# per-host:@{ub} begins the @{i}per-host@{ui} section.

   A line beginning with @{b}# per-target:@{ub} begins the @{i}per-target@{ui} section.

   If it exists, the @{i}post-target@{ui} section begins with @{b}# post-target:@{ub}.


 @{" configure variables   " link "configure variables"}  Variables available to configure.in
 @{" Minimal               " link "Minimal"}  A minimal configure.in
 @{" Declarations          " link "Declarations"}  For each invocation
 @{" per-host              " link "per-host"}  Host-specific instructions
 @{" per-target            " link "per-target"}  Target-specific instructions
 @{" post-target           " link "post-target"}  Instructions to be executed after target info
 @{" Example               " link "Example"}  An example configure.in


@endnode

@node "configure variables" "configure.guide/configure variables"
@next "Minimal"
@toc "configure.in"

Variables available to @{b}configure.in@{ub}
-----------------------------------

   The following variables pass information between the standard parts
of @{b}configure@{ub} and the shell-script fragments in @{b}configure.in@{ub}:

@{b}srctrigger@{ub}
     Contains the name of a source file that is expected to live in the
     source directory.  You must usually set this in the @{i}per-invocation@{ui}
     section of @{b}configure.in@{ub}.  @{b}configure@{ub} tests to see that this file
     exists.  If the file does not exist, @{b}configure@{ub} prints an error
     message.  This is used as a sanity check that @{b}configure.in@{ub} matches
     the source directory.

@{b}srcname@{ub}
     Contains the name of the source collection contained in the source
     directory.  You must usually set this in the @{i}per-invocation@{ui}
     section of @{b}configure.in@{ub}.  If the file named in @{b}srctrigger@{ub} does not
     exist, @{b}configure@{ub} uses the value of @{b}srcname@{ub} when it prints the error
     message.

@{b}configdirs@{ub}
     Contains the names of any subdirectories in which @{b}configure@{ub} should
     recurse.  You must usually set this in the @{i}per-invocation@{ui} section
     of @{b}configure.in@{ub}.  If @{b}Makefile.in@{ub} contains a line starting with
     @{b}SUBDIRS =@{ub}, then it will be replaced with an assignment to @{b}SUBDIRS@{ub}
     using the value of @{b}configdirs@{ub} (if @{b}subdirs@{ub} is empty).  This can be
     used to determine which directories to configure and build
     depending on the host and target configurations.  Use @{b}configdirs@{ub}
     (instead of the @{b}subdirs@{ub} variable described below) if you want to
     be able to partition the subdirectories, or use independent
     @{b}Makefile@{ub} fragments.  Each subdirectory can be independent, and
     independently reconfigured.

@{b}subdirs@{ub}
     Contains the names of any subdirectories where @{b}configure@{ub} should
     create a @{b}Makefile@{ub} (in addition to the current directory), @{i}without@{ui}
     recursively running @{b}configure@{ub}.  Use @{b}subdirs@{ub} (instead of the
     @{b}configdirs@{ub} variable described above) if you want to configure all
     of the directories as a unit.  Since there is a single invocation
     of @{b}configure@{ub} that configures many directories, all the directories
     can use the same @{b}Makefile@{ub} fragments, and the same @{b}configure.in@{ub}.

@{b}host@{ub}
     Contains the full configuration name for the host (generated by
     the script @{b}config.sub@{ub} from the name that you entered).  This is a
     three-part name (commonly referred to as a @{i}triple@{ui}) of the form
     CPU-VENDOR-OS.

     There are separate variables @{b}host_cpu@{ub}, @{b}host_vendor@{ub}, and @{b}host_os@{ub}
     that you can use to test each of the three parts; this variable is
     useful, however, for error messages, and for testing combinations
     of the three components.

@{b}host_cpu@{ub}
     Contains the first element of the canonical triple representing
     the host as returned by @{b}config.sub@{ub}.  This is occasionally used to
     distinguish between minor variations of a particular vendor's
     operating system and sometimes to determine variations in binary
     format between the host and the target.

@{b}host_vendor@{ub}
     Contains the second element of the canonical triple representing
     the host as returned by @{b}config.sub@{ub}.  This is usually used to
     distinguish among the numerous variations of @{i}common@{ui} operating
     systems.

@{b}host_os@{ub}
     Contains the the third element of the canonical triple
     representing the host as returned by @{b}config.sub@{ub}.

@{b}target@{ub}
     Contains the full configuration name (generated by the script
     @{b}config.sub@{ub} from the name that you entered) for the target.  Like
     the host, this is a three-part name of the form CPU-VENDOR-OS.

     There are separate variables @{b}target_cpu@{ub}, @{b}target_vendor@{ub}, and
     @{b}target_os@{ub} that you can use to test each of the three parts; this
     variable is useful, however, for error messages, and for testing
     combinations of the three components.

@{b}target_cpu@{ub}
     Contains the first element of the canonical triple representing
     the target as returned by @{b}config.sub@{ub}.  This variable is used
     heavily by programs which are involved in building other programs,
     like the compiler, assembler, linker, etc.  Most programs will not
     need the @{b}target@{ub} variables at all, but this one could conceivably
     be used to build a program, for instance, that operated on binary
     data files whose byte order or alignment differ from the system
     where the program is running.

@{b}target_vendor@{ub}
     Contains the second element of the canonical triple representing
     the target as returned by @{b}config.sub@{ub}.  This is usually used to
     distinguish among the numerous variations of @{i}common@{ui} operating
     systems or object file formats.  It is sometimes used to switch
     between different flavors of user interfaces.

@{b}target_os@{ub}
     Contains the the third element of the canonical triple
     representing the target as returned by @{b}config.sub@{ub}.  This variable
     is used by development tools to distinguish between subtle
     variations in object file formats that some vendors use across
     operating system releases.  It might also be use to decide which
     libraries to build or what user interface the tool should provide.

@{b}floating_point@{ub}
     Set to @{b}no@{ub} if you invoked @{b}configure@{ub} with the @{b}--nfp@{ub} command-line
     option, otherwise it is empty.  This is a request to target
     machines with @{i}no floating point@{ui} unit, even if the targets
     ordinarily have floating point units available.

@{b}gas@{ub}
     Set to @{b}true@{ub} if you invoked @{b}configure@{ub} with the @{b}--with-gnu-as@{ub}
     command line option, otherwise it is empty.  This is a request to
     assume that the specified HOSTTYPE machine has GNU @{b}as@{ub} available
     even if it ordinarily does not.

@{b}srcdir@{ub}
     Set to the name of the directory containing the source for this
     program.  This will be different from @{b}.@{ub} if you have specified the
     @{b}--srcdir=DIR@{ub} option.  @{b}srcdir@{ub} can indicate either an absolute path
     or a path relative to the build directory.

@{b}package_makefile_frag@{ub}
     If set in @{b}configure.in@{ub}, this variable should be the name a file
     relative to @{b}srcdir@{ub} to be included in the resulting @{b}Makefile@{ub}.  If
     the named file does not exist, @{b}configure@{ub} will print a warning
     message.  This variable is not set by @{b}configure@{ub}.

@{b}host_makefile_frag@{ub}
     If set in @{b}configure.in@{ub}, this variable should be the name a file
     relative to @{b}srcdir@{ub} to be included in the resulting @{b}Makefile@{ub}.  If
     the named file does not exist, @{b}configure@{ub} will print a warning
     message.  This variable is not set by @{b}configure@{ub}.

@{b}target_makefile_frag@{ub}
     If set in @{b}configure.in@{ub}, this variable should be the name of a file,
     relative to @{b}srcdir@{ub}, to be included in the resulting @{b}Makefile@{ub}.  If
     the named file does not exist, @{b}configure@{ub} will print a warning
     message.  This variable is not set by @{b}configure@{ub}.

@{b}site_makefile_frag@{ub}
     Set to a file name representing to the default @{b}Makefile@{ub} fragment
     for this host.  It may be set in @{b}configure.in@{ub} to override this
     default.  Normally @{b}site_makefile_frag@{ub} is empty, but will have a
     value if you specify @{b}--site=SITE@{ub} on the command line.

@{b}Makefile@{ub}
     Set to the name of the generated @{b}Makefile@{ub}.  Normally this value is
     precisely @{b}Makefile@{ub}, but some programs may want something else.

@{b}removing@{ub}
     Normally empty but will be set to some non-null value if you
     specified @{b}--rm@{ub} on the command line.  That is, if @{b}removing@{ub} is not
     empty, then @{b}configure@{ub} is @{i}removing@{ui} a configuration rather than
     creating one.

@{b}files@{ub}
     If this variable is not empty following the @{i}per-target@{ui} section,
     then each word in its value will be the target of a symbolic link
     named in the corresponding word from the @{b}links@{ub} variable.

@{b}links@{ub}
     If the @{b}files@{ub} variable is not empty following the @{i}per-target@{ui}
     section, then @{b}configure@{ub} creates symbolic links with the first word
     of @{b}links@{ub} pointing to the first word of @{b}files@{ub}, the second word of
     @{b}links@{ub} pointing to the second word of @{b}files@{ub}, and so on.


@endnode

@node "Minimal" "configure.guide/Minimal"
@next "Declarations"
@prev "configure variables"
@toc "configure.in"

A minimal @{b}configure.in@{ub}
----------------------

   A minimal @{b}configure.in@{ub} consists of four lines.

     srctrigger=foo.c
     srcname="source for the foo program"
     # per-host:
     # per-target:

   The @{b}# per-host:@{ub} and @{b}# per-target:@{ub} lines divide the file into the
three required sections.  The @{b}srctrigger@{ub} line names a file.  @{b}configure@{ub}
checks to see that this file exists in the source directory before
configuring.  If the @{b}srctrigger@{ub} file does not exist, @{b}configure@{ub} uses the
value of @{b}srcname@{ub} to print an error message about not finding the source.

   This particular example uses no links, and only the default host,
target, and site-specific @{b}Makefile@{ub} fragments if they exist.


@endnode

@node "Declarations" "configure.guide/Declarations"
@next "per-host"
@prev "Minimal"
@toc "configure.in"

For each invocation
-------------------

@{b}   configure@{ub} invokes the entire shell script fragment from the start of
@{b}configure.in@{ub} up to a line beginning with @{b}# per-host:@{ub} immediately after
parsing command line arguments.  The variables @{b}srctrigger@{ub} and @{b}srcname@{ub}
@{i}must@{ui} be set here.

   You might also want to set the variables @{b}configdirs@{ub} and
@{b}package_makefile_frag@{ub} here.


@endnode

@node "per-host" "configure.guide/per-host"
@next "per-target"
@prev "Declarations"
@toc "configure.in"

Host-specific instructions
--------------------------

   The @{i}per-host@{ui} section of @{b}configure.in@{ub} starts with the line that
begins with @{b}# per-host:@{ub} and ends before a line beginning with
@{b}# per-target:@{ub}.  @{b}configure@{ub} invokes the commands in the @{i}per-host@{ui} section
when determining host-specific information.

   This section usually contains a big @{b}case@{ub} statement using the variable
@{b}host@{ub} to determine appropriate values for @{b}host_makefile_frag@{ub} and @{b}files@{ub},
although @{b}files@{ub} is not usually set here.  Usually, it is set at the end
of the @{i}per-target@{ui} section after determining the names of the target
specific configuration files.


@endnode

@node "per-target" "configure.guide/per-target"
@next "post-target"
@prev "per-host"
@toc "configure.in"

Target-specific instructions
----------------------------

   The @{i}per-target@{ui} section of @{b}configure.in@{ub} starts with the line that
begins with @{b}# per-target:@{ub} and ends before the line that begins with
@{b}# post-target:@{ub}, if there is such a line.  Otherwise the @{i}per-target@{ui}
section extends to the end of the file.  @{b}configure@{ub} invokes the commands
in the @{i}per-target@{ui} section when determining target-specific information,
and before building any files, directories, or links.

   This section usually contains a big @{b}case@{ub} statement using the variable
@{b}target@{ub} to determine appropriate values for @{b}target_makefile_frag@{ub} and
@{b}files@{ub}.  The last lines in the @{i}per-target@{ui} section normally set the
variables @{b}files@{ub} and @{b}links@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "post-target" "configure.guide/post-target"
@next "Example"
@prev "per-target"
@toc "configure.in"

Instructions to be executed after target info
---------------------------------------------

   The @{i}post-target@{ui} section is optional.  If it exists, the @{b}post-target@{ub}
section starts with a line beginning with @{b}# Post-target:@{ub} and extends to
the end of the file.  If it exists, @{b}configure@{ub} invokes this section once
for each target after building all files, directories, or links.

   This section is seldom needed, but you can use it to edit the
@{b}Makefile@{ub} generated by @{b}configure@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "Example" "configure.guide/Example"
@prev "post-target"
@toc "configure.in"

An example @{b}configure.in@{ub}
-----------------------

   Here is a small example of a @{b}configure.in@{ub} file.

     # This file is a collection of shell script fragments
     # used to tailor a template configure script as
     # appropriate for this directory.  For more information,
     # see configure.texi.
     
     configdirs=
     srctrigger=warshall.c
     srcname="bison"
     
     # per-host:
     case "${host}" in
     m88k-motorola-*)
             host_makefile_frag=config/mh-delta88
             ;;
     esac
     
     # per-target:
     files="bison_in.hairy"
     links="bison.hairy"
     
     # post-target:


@endnode

@node "Install locations" "configure.guide/Install locations"
@next "Host"
@prev "configure.in"
@toc "Using configure"

Install locations
=================

   Using the default configuration, @{b}make install@{ub} creates a single tree
of files, some of which are programs.  The location of this tree is
determined by the value of the variable @{b}prefix@{ub}.  The default value of
@{b}prefix@{ub} is @{b}/gg@{ub}.  This is often correct for native tools installed on only
one host.


 @{" prefix           " link "prefix"}  Changing the default install directory
 @{" exec_prefix      " link "exec_prefix"}  How to separate host independent files
                                         from host dependent files when
                                         installing for multiple hosts
 @{" Install details  " link "Install details"}  Full descriptions of all installation subdirectories


@endnode

@node "prefix" "configure.guide/prefix"
@next "exec_prefix"
@toc "Install locations"

Changing the default install directory
--------------------------------------

   In the default configuration, all files are installed in
subdirectories of @{b}/gg@{ub}.  The location is determined by the value of the
@{b}configure@{ub} variable @{b}prefix@{ub}; in turn, this determines the value of the
@{b}Makefile@{ub} variable of the same name (@{b}prefix@{ub}).

   You can also set the value of the @{b}Makefile@{ub} variable @{b}prefix@{ub}
explicitly each time you invoke @{b}make@{ub} if you are so inclined.  However,
because many programs have this location compiled in, you must specify
the @{b}prefix@{ub} value consistently on each invocation of @{b}make@{ub}, or you will
end up with a broken installation.

   To make this easier, the value of the @{b}configure@{ub} variable @{b}prefix@{ub} can
be set on the command line to @{b}configure@{ub} using the option @{b}--prefix=@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "exec_prefix" "configure.guide/exec_prefix"
@next "Install details"
@prev "prefix"
@toc "Install locations"

Installing for multiple hosts
-----------------------------

   By default, host dependent files are installed in subdirectories of
@{b}$(exec_prefix)@{ub}.  The location is determined by the value of the
@{b}configure@{ub} variable @{b}exec_prefix@{ub}, which determines the value of the
@{b}Makefile@{ub} variable @{b}exec_prefix@{ub}.  This makes it easier to install for a
single host, and simplifies changing the default location for the
install tree.  The default doesn't allow for multiple hosts to
effectively share host independent files, however.

   To configure so that multiple hosts can share common files, use
something like:

     configure HOST1 -prefix=/usr/gnu -exec_prefix=/usr/gnu/H-host1
     make all info install install-info clean
     
     configure HOST2 -prefix=/usr/gnu -exec_prefix=/usr/gnu/H-host2
     make all info install install-info

   The first line configures the source for HOST1 to place host-specific
programs in subdirectories of @{b}/usr/gnu/H-HOST1@{ub}.

   The second line builds and installs all programs for HOST1,
including both host-independent and host-specific files, as well as
removing the host-specific object files from of the build directory.

   The third line reconfigures the source for HOST2 to place host
specific programs in subdirectories of @{b}/usr/gnu/H-HOST2@{ub}.

   The fourth line builds and installs all programs for HOST2.  Host
specific files are installed in new directories, but the host
independent files are installed @{i}on top of@{ui} the host independent files
installed for HOST1.  This results in a single copy of the host
independent files, suitable for use by both hosts.

   See @{"Extensions to the GNU coding standards" link "Makefile extensions"}, for more information.


@endnode

@node "Install details" "configure.guide/Install details"
@prev "exec_prefix"
@toc "Install locations"

Full descriptions of all installation subdirectories
----------------------------------------------------

   During any install, a number of standard directories are created.
Their names are determined by @{b}Makefile@{ub} variables.  Some of the defaults
for @{b}Makefile@{ub} variables can be changed at configuration time using
command line options to @{b}configure@{ub}.  For more information on the standard
directories or the @{b}Makefile@{ub} variables, please refer to
@{"Makefile Conventions" link "standards.guide/Makefiles"}.  See also
@{"Extensions to the GNU coding standards" link "Makefile extensions"}.

   Note that @{b}configure@{ub} does not create the directory indicated by the
variable @{b}srcdir@{ub} at any time.  @{b}$(srcdir)@{ub} is not an installation
directory.

   You can override all @{b}Makefile@{ub} variables on the command line to @{b}make@{ub}.
(See @{"Overriding Variables" link "make.guide/Overriding"}.)  If you do so, you will need to specify
the value precisely the same way for each invocation of @{b}make@{ub}, or you
risk ending up with a broken installation.  This is because many
programs have the locations of other programs or files compiled into
them.  If you find yourself overriding any of the variables frequently,
you should consider site dependent @{b}Makefile@{ub} fragments.  See also
@{"Adding site info" link "Sites"}.

   During @{b}make install@{ub}, a number of standard directories are created and
populated.  The following @{b}Makefile@{ub} variables define them.  Those whose
defaults are set by corresponding @{b}configure@{ub} variables are marked
"@{b}Makefile@{ub} and @{b}configure@{ub}".

@{b}prefix (@{b}Makefile@{ub} and @{b}configure@{ub})@{ub}
     The root of the installation tree.  You can set its @{b}Makefile@{ub}
     default with the @{b}--prefix=@{ub} command line option to @{b}configure@{ub} (see
     @{"Invoking configure" link "Invoking configure"}).  The default value for @{b}prefix@{ub} is @{b}/gg@{ub}.

@{b}bindir@{ub}
     A directory for binary programs that users can run.  The default
     value for @{b}bindir@{ub} depends on @{b}prefix@{ub}; @{b}bindir@{ub} is normally changed only
     indirectly through @{b}prefix@{ub}.  The default value for @{b}bindir@{ub} is
     @{b}$(prefix)/bin@{ub}.

@{b}exec_prefix (@{b}Makefile@{ub} and @{b}configure@{ub})@{ub}
     A directory for host dependent files.  You can specify the @{b}Makefile@{ub}
     default value by using the @{b}--exec_prefix=@{ub} option to @{b}configure@{ub}.
     (See @{"Invoking configure" link "Invoking configure"}.)  The default value for @{b}exec_prefix@{ub} is
     @{b}$(prefix)@{ub}.

@{b}libdir@{ub}
     A directory for libraries and support programs.  The default value
     for @{b}libdir@{ub} depends on @{b}prefix@{ub}; @{b}libdir@{ub} is normally changed only
     indirectly through @{b}prefix@{ub}.  The default value for @{b}libdir@{ub} is
     @{b}$(prefix)/lib@{ub}.

@{b}mandir@{ub}
     A directory for @{b}man@{ub} format documentation ("man pages").  The
     default value for @{b}mandir@{ub} depends on @{b}prefix@{ub}; @{b}mandir@{ub} is normally
     changed only indirectly through @{b}prefix@{ub}.  The default value for
     @{b}mandir@{ub} is @{b}$(prefix)/man@{ub}.

@{b}manNdir@{ub}
     These are eight variables named @{b}man1dir@{ub}, @{b}man2dir@{ub}, etc.  They name
     the specific directories for each man page section.  For example,
     @{b}man1dir@{ub} by default holds the filename @{b}$(mandir)/man1@{ub}; this
     directory contains @{b}emacs.1@{ub} (the man page for GNU Emacs).
     Similarly, @{b}man5dir@{ub} contains the value @{b}$(mandir)/man5@{ub}, indicating
     the directory which holds @{b}rcsfile.5@{ub} (the man page describing the
     @{b}rcs@{ub} data file format).  The default value for any of the @{b}manNdir@{ub}
     variables depends indirectly on @{b}prefix@{ub}, and is normally changed
     only through @{b}prefix@{ub}.  The default value for @{b}manNdir@{ub} is
     @{b}$(mandir)/manN@{ub}.

@{b}manNext@{ub}
@{i}     Not supported by Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub}@{ui}.  The `GNU Coding Standards' do
     not call for @{b}man1ext@{ub}, @{b}man2ext@{ub}, so the intended use for @{b}manext@{ub} is
     apparently not parallel to @{b}mandir@{ub}.  Its use is not clear.  (See
     also @{"Extensions to the GNU coding standards" link "Makefile extensions"}.)

@{b}infodir@{ub}
     A directory for @{b}info@{ub} format documentation.  The default value for
     @{b}infodir@{ub} depends indirectly on @{b}prefix@{ub}; @{b}infodir@{ub} is normally changed
     only through @{b}prefix@{ub}.  The default value for @{b}infodir@{ub} is
     @{b}$(prefix)/info@{ub}.

@{b}docdir@{ub}
     A directory for any documentation that is in a format other than
     those used by @{b}info@{ub} or @{b}man@{ub}.  The default value for @{b}docdir@{ub} depends
     indirectly on @{b}prefix@{ub}; @{b}docdir@{ub} is normally changed only through
     @{b}prefix@{ub}.  The default value for @{b}docdir@{ub} is @{b}$(datadir)/doc@{ub}.  @{i}This
     variable is an extension to the GNU coding standards@{ui}.  (See also
     @{"Extensions to the GNU coding standards" link "Makefile extensions"}.)

@{b}includedir@{ub}
     A directory for the header files accompanying the libraries
     installed in @{b}libdir@{ub}.  The default value for @{b}includedir@{ub} depends on
     @{b}prefix@{ub}; @{b}includedir@{ub} is normally changed only indirectly through
     @{b}prefix@{ub}.  The default value for @{b}includedir@{ub} is @{b}$(prefix)/include@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "Host" "configure.guide/Host"
@next "Target"
@prev "Install locations"
@toc "Using configure"

Host
====

   The arguments to @{b}configure@{ub} are @{i}hosttypes@{ui}.  By @{i}hosttype@{ui} we mean the
@{i}environment@{ui} in which the source will be compiled.  This need not
necessarily be the same as the physical machine involved, although it
usually is.

   For example, if some obscure machine had the GNU @{b}POSIX@{ub} emulation
libraries available, it would be possible to configure most GNU source
for a @{b}POSIX@{ub} system and build it on the obscure host.

   For more on this topic, see @{"On Configuring Development Tools" link "cfg-paper.guide/Host Environments"}.


@endnode

@node "Target" "configure.guide/Target"
@next "Makefile fragments"
@prev "Host"
@toc "Using configure"

Target
======

   For building native development tools, or most of the other GNU
tools, you need not worry about the target.  The @{i}target@{ui} of a
configuration defaults to the same as the @{i}host@{ui}.

   For building cross development tools, please see
@{"On Configuring Development Tools" link "cfg-paper.guide/Building Development Environments"}.


@endnode

@node "Makefile fragments" "configure.guide/Makefile fragments"
@next "Makefile extensions"
@prev "Target"
@toc "Using configure"

Adding information about local conventions
==========================================

   If you find that a tool does not get configured to your liking, or if
@{b}configure@{ub}'s conventions differ from your local conventions, you should
probably consider @{i}site-specific @{b}Makefile@{ub} fragments@{ui}.  See also
@{"Adding site info" link "Sites"}.

   These are probably not the right choice for options that can be set
from the @{b}configure@{ub} command line or for differences that are host or
target dependent.

   Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub} uses three types of @{b}Makefile@{ub} fragments.  In a
generated @{b}Makefile@{ub} they appear in the order: @{i}target fragment@{ui}, @{i}host
fragment@{ui}, and @{i}site fragment@{ui}.  This allows host fragments to override
target fragments, and site fragments to override both.

   Host-specific @{b}Makefile@{ub} fragments conventionally reside in the
@{b}./config/@{ub} subdirectory with names of the form @{b}mh-HOSTTYPE@{ub}.  They are
used for hosts that require odd options to the standard compiler and
for compile time options based on the host configuration.

   Target-specific @{b}Makefile@{ub} fragments conventionally reside in the
@{b}./config/@{ub} subdirectory with names of the form @{b}mt-TARGET@{ub}.  They are used
for target dependent compile time options.

   Site specific @{b}Makefile@{ub} fragments conventionally reside in the
@{b}./config/@{ub} subdirectory with names of the form @{b}ms-SITE@{ub}.  They are used
to override host- and target-independent compile time options.  Note
that you can also override these options on the @{b}make@{ub} invocation line.


@endnode

@node "Makefile extensions" "configure.guide/Makefile extensions"
@prev "Makefile fragments"
@toc "Using configure"

Extensions to the GNU coding standards
======================================

   The following additions to the GNU coding standards are required for
Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub} to work properly.

   * The @{b}Makefile@{ub} must contain exactly one line starting with @{b}####@{ub}.
     This line should follow any default macro definitions but precede
     any rules.  Host, target, and site-specific @{b}Makefile@{ub} fragments
     will be inserted immediately after this line.  If the line is
     missing, the fragments will not be inserted.

   * Cygnus adds the following targets to each @{b}Makefile@{ub}.  Their
     existence is not required for Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub}, but they are
     documented here for completeness.

    @{b}info@{ub}
          Build all info files from texinfo source.

    @{b}install-info@{ub}
          Install all info files.

    @{b}clean-info@{ub}
          Remove all info files and any intermediate files that can be
          generated from texinfo source.

    @{b}Makefile@{ub}
          Calls @{b}./config.status@{ub} to rebuild the @{b}Makefile@{ub} in this
          directory.

   * The following @{b}Makefile@{ub} targets have revised semantics:

    @{b}install@{ub}
          Should @{i}not@{ui} depend on the target @{b}all@{ub}.  If the program is not
          already built, @{b}make install@{ub} should fail.  This allows you to
          install programs even when @{b}make@{ub} would otherwise determine
          them to be out of date.  This can happen, for example, when
          the result of a @{b}make all@{ub} is transported via tape to another
          machine for installation.

    @{b}clean@{ub}
          Should remove any file that can be regenerated by the
          @{b}Makefile@{ub}, excepting only the @{b}Makefile@{ub} itself, and any links
          created by @{b}configure@{ub}.  That is, @{b}make all clean@{ub} should return
          all directories to their original condition.  If this is not
          done, then the command sequence

               configure HOST1 ; make all install clean ;
               configure HOST2 ; make all install

          will fail because of intermediate files intended for HOST1.

   * Cygnus adds the following macros to all @{b}Makefile.in@{ub} files, but you
     are not required to use them to run Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub}.

    @{b}docdir@{ub}
          The directory in which to install any documentation that is
          not either a @{b}man@{ub} page or an @{b}info@{ub} file.  For @{b}man@{ub} pages, see
          @{b}mandir@{ub}; for @{b}info@{ub}, see @{b}infodir@{ub}.

    @{b}includedir@{ub}
          The directory in which to install any header files that
          should be made available to users.  This is distinct from the
          @{b}gcc@{ub} include directory, which is intended for @{b}gcc@{ub} only.  Files
          in @{b}includedir@{ub} may be used by @{b}cc@{ub} as well.

   * The following macros have revised semantics.  Most of them describe
     installation directories; see also
     @{"Full description of all installation subdirectories" link "Install details"}.

    @{b}datadir@{ub}
          is used for host independent data files.

    @{b}mandir@{ub}
          The default path for @{b}mandir@{ub} depends on @{b}prefix@{ub}.

    @{b}infodir@{ub}
          The default path for @{b}infodir@{ub} depends on @{b}prefix@{ub}.

    @{b}BISON@{ub}
          is assumed to have a @{b}yacc@{ub} calling convention.  To use GNU
          @{b}bison@{ub}, use @{b}BISON=bison -y@{ub}.

   * Each Cygnus @{b}Makefile@{ub} also conforms to one additional restriction:

     When libraries are installed, the line containing the call to
     @{b}INSTALL_DATA@{ub} should always be followed by a line containing a call
     to @{b}RANLIB@{ub} on the installed library.  This is to accommodate
     systems that use @{b}ranlib@{ub}.  Systems that do not use @{b}ranlib@{ub} can set
     @{b}RANLIB@{ub} to "@{b}echo@{ub}" in a host specific @{b}Makefile@{ub} fragment.


@endnode

