Porting with @{b}configure@{ub}
**********************

   This section explains how to add programs, host and target
configuration names, and site-specific information to Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub}.


 @{" Programs              " link "Programs"}  Adding configure to new programs
 @{" Hosts and targets     " link "Hosts and targets"}  Adding hosts and targets
 @{" Sites                 " link "Sites"}  Adding site info


@endnode

@node "Programs" "configure.guide/Programs"
@next "Hosts and targets"
@toc "Porting"

Adding @{b}configure@{ub} to new programs
================================

   If you are writing a new program, you probably shouldn't worry about
porting or configuration issues until it is running reasonably on some
host.  Then refer back to this section.

   If your program currently has a @{b}configure@{ub} script that meets the GNU
standards (see @{"How Configuration Should Work" link "standards.guide/Configuration"}, please do not add Cygnus
@{b}configure@{ub}.  It should be possible to add this program without change to
a Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub} style source tree.

   If the program is not target dependent, please consider using
@{b}autoconf@{ub} instead of Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub}.  @{b}autoconf@{ub} is available from the
Free Software Foundation; it is a program which generates an executable
shell script called @{b}configure@{ub} by automatically finding information on
the system to be configured on and embedding this information in the
shell script.  @{b}configure@{ub} scripts generated by @{b}autoconf@{ub} require no
arguments, and accept the same options as Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub}.  For
detailed instructions on using @{b}autoconf@{ub}, see
@{"How to organize and produce Autoconf scripts" link "autoconf.guide/Making configure Scripts"}.

   To add Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub} to an existing program, do the following:

*Make sure the @{b}Makefile@{ub} conforms to the GNU standard
     The coding standard for writing a GNU @{b}Makefile@{ub} is described in
     @{"Makefile Conventions" link "standards.guide/Makefiles"}.  For technical information on writing a
     @{b}Makefile@{ub}, see @{"Writing Makefiles" link "make.guide/Makefiles"}.

*Add Cygnus extensions to the @{b}Makefile@{ub}
     These are described in @{"Extensions to the GNU coding standards" link "Makefile extensions"}.

*Collect package specific definitions in a single file
     Many packages are best configured using a common @{b}Makefile@{ub} fragment
     which is included by all of the makefiles in the different
     directories of the package.  In order to accomplish this, set the
     variable @{b}package_makefile_fragment@{ub} to the name of the file.  It
     will be inserted into the final @{b}Makefile@{ub} before the
     target-specific fragment.

*Move host support from @{b}Makefile@{ub} to fragments
     This usually involves finding sections of the @{b}Makefile@{ub} that say
     things like "uncomment these lines for host HOSTTYPE" and moving
     them to a new file called @{b}./config/mh-HOSTTYPE@{ub}. For more
     information, see @{"Adding hosts and targets" link "Hosts and targets"}.

*Choose defaults
     If the program has compile-time options that determine the way the
     program should behave, choose reasonable defaults and make these
     @{b}Makefile@{ub} variables.  Be sure the variables are assigned their
     default values before the @{b}####@{ub} line so that site-specific @{b}Makefile@{ub}
     fragments can override them (see
     @{"Extensions to the GNU coding standards" link "Makefile extensions"}).

*Locate configuration files
     If there is configuration information in header files or source
     files, separate it in such a way that the files have generic
     names.  Then move the specific instances of those files into the
     @{b}./config/@{ub} subdirectory.

*Separate host and target information
     Some programs already have this information separated.  If yours
     does not, you will need to separate these two kinds of
     configuration information.  @{i}Host specific@{ui} information is the
     information needed to compile the program.  @{i}Target specific@{ui}
     information is information on the format of data files that the
     program will read or write.  This information should live in
     separate files in the @{b}./config/@{ub} subdirectory with names that
     reflect the configuration for which they are intended.

     At this point you might skip this step and simply move on.  If you
     do, you should end up with a program that can be configured only
     to build @{i}native@{ui} tools, that is, tools for which the host system is
     also the target system.  Later, you could attempt to build a cross
     tool and separate out the target-specific information by figuring
     out what went wrong.  This is often simpler than combing through
     all of the source code.

*Write @{b}configure.in@{ub}
     Usually this involves writing shell script fragments to map from
     canonical configuration names into the names of the configuration
     files.  These files will then be linked at configure time from the
     specific instances of those files in @{b}./config@{ub} to files in the
     build directory with more generic names.  (See also
     @{"Build directories" link "Build directories"}.)  The format of @{b}configure.in@{ub} is described in
     @{"The configure.in input file" link "configure.in"}.

*Rename @{b}Makefile@{ub} to @{b}Makefile.in@{ub}
   At this point you should have a program that can be configured using
Cygnus @{b}configure@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "Hosts and targets" "configure.guide/Hosts and targets"
@next "Sites"
@prev "Programs"
@toc "Porting"

Adding hosts and targets
========================

   To add a host or target to a program that already uses Cygnus
@{b}configure@{ub}, do the following.

   * Make sure the new configuration name is represented in @{b}config.sub@{ub}.
     If not, add it.  For more details, see the comments in the shell
     script @{b}config.sub@{ub}.

   * If you are adding a host configuration, look in @{b}configure.in@{ub}, in
     the @{i}per-host@{ui} section.  Make sure that your configuration name is
     represented in the mapping from host configuration names to
     configuration files.  If not, add it.  Also see
     @{"The configure.in input file" link "configure.in"}.

   * If you are adding a target configuration, look in @{b}configure.in@{ub}, in
     the @{i}per-target@{ui} section.  Make sure that your configuration name is
     represented in the mapping from target configuration names to
     configuration files.  If not, add it.  Also see
     @{"The configure.in input file" link "configure.in"}.

   * Look in @{b}configure.in@{ub} for the variables @{b}files@{ub}, @{b}links@{ub},
     @{b}host_makefile_frag@{ub}, and @{b}target_makefile_frag@{ub}.  The values assigned
     to these variables are the names of the configuration files,
     (relative to @{b}srcdir@{ub}) that the program uses.  Make sure that copies
     of the files exist for your host.  If not, create them.  See also
     @{"Variables available to configure.in" link "configure variables"}.

   This should be enough to @{b}configure@{ub} for a new host or target
configuration name.  Getting the program to compile and run properly
represents the hardest work of any port.


@endnode

@node "Sites" "configure.guide/Sites"
@prev "Hosts and targets"
@toc "Porting"

Adding site info
================

   If some of the @{b}Makefile@{ub} defaults are not right for your site, you can
build site-specific @{b}Makefile@{ub} fragments.  To do this, do the following.

   * Choose a name for your site.  It must currently be less than
     eleven characters.

   * If the program source does not have a @{b}./config/@{ub} subdirectory,
     create it.

   * Create a file called @{b}./config/ms-SITE@{ub} where SITE is the name of
     your site.  In it, set whatever @{b}Makefile@{ub} variables you need to
     override to match your site's conventions.

   * Configure the program with:

          configure ... --site=SITE


@endnode

